        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 37-year-old woman in the Czech Republic who comes in describing recurrent retrosternal burning after meals and episodes of sour-tasting fluid coming back up into her chest and throat, symptoms that fit the typical pattern of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease [PMID:9861914]. She says the discomfort is felt as heartburn in the chest and sometimes as precordial pain, and she has also noticed an irritating cough on some days [SNOMED:K21.9]. The symptoms have been going on for months and feel chronic rather than isolated, which is common for this condition [PMID:9861914].\n\nShe appears tired from broken sleep because the burning often wakes her at night with heartburn, and she keeps over-the-counter antacids at home for temporary relief [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She has started drinking water after swallowing when the chest burning flares and has begun avoiding some meals because eating can bring on the pain [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She denies red-flag complaints such as trouble swallowing, painful swallowing, weight loss, or known anaemia [PMID:9861914].\n\n{patientName} works a desk-based administrative job and says busy periods increase her stress, which seems to worsen symptoms; she also notices more reflux after large, spicy, or junk-food meals [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She lives with her partner, enjoys weekend walks and cooking, and has recently tried eating smaller, more frequent meals and sleeping with extra pillows to reduce nighttime reflux [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She does not report heavy alcohol use or smoking, but she is aware these habits can aggravate reflux and has been trying to keep to a healthier routine [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:93cd6433-5687-4f02-a789-115aec8a39d8",
      "resource": {
