        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports several months of recurrent heartburn and acidic regurgitation, especially after meals and when lying down at night, with occasional chest burning during swallowing and intermittent cough [PMID:9861914; SNOMED:K21.9; MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She says over-the-counter antacids help somewhat, but symptoms recur frequently, suggesting a chronic pattern [PMID:9861914; MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She has not had prior hospitalization for this problem and has no known history of dysphagia, odynophagia, weight loss, or anaemia, which lowers concern for alarm features at presentation [PMID:9861914].\n\nLifestyle review is notable for symptom triggers with large meals, spicy food, junk food, stress, and nighttime recumbency [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She has started making practical changes including smaller frequent meals, elevating her head with extra pillows, and avoiding late heavy meals [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She is not currently known to have other major comorbidities. There is no previous reflux procedure, but she understands that patients who do not respond to conventional medical therapy may need further work-up and, in selected resistant cases, surgery [PMID:27405413]."
          }
        ]
      }
